# Intune Module Data Generation
*(Christian Stohlmann)*

Uses the old Intune Devices CSV to try and generate more realistic data.

This does notebook basically does the same thing as the old notebook "Intune Module Data Processing", 
except for now has the updated Devices so that IDs and now replaced with UPNs.

There are also some other other sample data lines hardcoded in order to simulate realistic data a little better.

from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType, DoubleType, ArrayType, TimestampType
from pyspark.sql.functions import *
from pyspark.sql.window import Window
import datetime

# data lake and container information
storage_account = 'stoeadaihackathon'
use_test_env = False

if use_test_env:
    stage1np = 'abfss://test-env@' + storage_account + '.dfs.core.windows.net/stage1np'
    stage2np = 'abfss://test-env@' + storage_account + '.dfs.core.windows.net/stage2np'
    stage2p = 'abfss://test-env@' + storage_account + '.dfs.core.windows.net/stage2p'
else:
    stage1np = 'abfss://stage1np@' + storage_account + '.dfs.core.windows.net'
    stage2np = 'abfss://stage2np@' + storage_account + '.dfs.core.windows.net'
    stage2p = 'abfss://stage2p@' + storage_account + '.dfs.core.windows.net'

# Method for replacing the OldIntuneDevices column "UPNs" to not include IDs, and also randomize those devices to be someone else's. 
num_of_devices = dfOldIntuneDevices.count()
isolated_UPNs = dfUsers.select('userPrincipalName').collect()
list_of_deviceNames = dfOldIntuneDevices.select('DeviceName').collect()
list_of_managedBys = dfOldIntuneDevices.select('ManagedBy').collect()
list_of_ownerships = dfOldIntuneDevices.select('Ownership').collect()
list_of_compliances = dfOldIntuneDevices.select('Compliance').collect()
list_of_OSs = dfOldIntuneDevices.select('OS').collect()
list_of_OSVersions = dfOldIntuneDevices.select('OSVersion').collect()
list_of_lastCheckIns = dfOldIntuneDevices.select('LastCheckIn').collect()
list_of_primaryUserUPNs = dfOldIntuneDevices.select('PrimaryUserUPN').collect()
list_of_deviceIDs = dfOldIntuneDevices.select('DeviceID').collect()

dfOldIntuneDevices = dfOldIntuneDevices.withColumn('randomNumbers', ceil(rand()*100))
list_of_randomNumbers = dfOldIntuneDevices.select('randomNumbers').collect()

devicesSchema = StructType(fields=[
    StructField('DeviceName', StringType(), False),
    StructField('ManagedBy', StringType(), False),
    StructField('Ownership', StringType(), False),
    StructField('Compliance', StringType(), False),
    StructField('OS', StringType(), False),
    StructField('OSVersion', StringType(), False),
    StructField('LastCheckIn', TimestampType(), False),
    StructField('PrimaryUserUPN', StringType(), False),
    StructField('DeviceID', StringType(), False)
])

dfNewDevicesGen = spark.createDataFrame([], devicesSchema)

UPNPlaceHolder = 0

for n in range(num_of_devices):
    # Updates UPNs without IDs and randomizes them
    if list_of_primaryUserUPNs[n][0] != isolated_UPNs[UPNPlaceHolder][0]:
        # Updates Ownerships to say "school" instead of "corporate"
        if list_of_ownerships[n][0] == "Corporate":
            randomNumber = list_of_randomNumbers[n][0]

            deviceName = list_of_deviceNames[n][0]
            managedBy = list_of_managedBys[n][0]
            compliance = list_of_compliances[n][0]
            oS = list_of_OSs[n][0]
            oSVersion = list_of_OSVersions[n][0]
            lastCheckIn = list_of_lastCheckIns[n][0]
            primaryUserUPN = isolated_UPNs[randomNumber][0]
            deviceID = list_of_deviceIDs[n][0]
            newRow = spark.createDataFrame([(deviceName, managedBy, 'School', compliance, '', oSVersion, lastCheckIn, primaryUserUPN, deviceID)])
        
            dfNewDevicesGen = dfNewDevicesGen.union(newRow)
            UPNPlaceHolder = UPNPlaceHolder + 1
        else: 
            randomNumber = list_of_randomNumbers[n][0]

            deviceName = list_of_deviceNames[n][0]
            managedBy = list_of_managedBys[n][0]
            ownership = list_of_ownerships[n][0]
            compliance = list_of_compliances[n][0]
            oS = list_of_OSs[n][0]
            oSVersion = list_of_OSVersions[n][0]
            lastCheckIn = list_of_lastCheckIns[n][0]
            primaryUserUPN = isolated_UPNs[randomNumber][0]
            deviceID = list_of_deviceIDs[n][0]
            newRow = spark.createDataFrame([(deviceName, managedBy, ownership, compliance, '', oSVersion, lastCheckIn, primaryUserUPN, deviceID)])
        
            dfNewDevicesGen = dfNewDevicesGen.union(newRow)
            UPNPlaceHolder = UPNPlaceHolder + 1

    elif list_of_ownerships[n][0] == "Corporate":
        deviceName = list_of_deviceNames[n][0]
        managedBy = list_of_managedBys[n][0]
        compliance = list_of_compliances[n][0]
        oS = list_of_OSs[n][0]
        oSVersion = list_of_OSVersions[n][0]
        lastCheckIn = list_of_lastCheckIns[n][0]
        primaryUserUPN = list_of_primaryUserUPNs[n][0]
        deviceID = list_of_deviceIDs[n][0]
        newRow = spark.createDataFrame([(deviceName, managedBy, 'School', compliance, '', oSVersion, lastCheckIn, primaryUserUPN, deviceID)])
        
        dfNewDevicesGen = dfNewDevicesGen.union(newRow)
    
    else: 
        deviceName = list_of_deviceNames[n][0]
        managedBy = list_of_managedBys[n][0]
        ownership = list_of_ownerships[n][0]
        compliance = list_of_compliances[n][0]
        oS = list_of_OSs[n][0]
        oSVersion = list_of_OSVersions[n][0]
        lastCheckIn = list_of_lastCheckIns[n][0]
        primaryUserUPN = list_of_primaryUserUPNs[n][0]
        deviceID = list_of_deviceIDs[n][0]
        newRow = spark.createDataFrame([(deviceName, managedBy, ownership, compliance, '', oSVersion, lastCheckIn, primaryUserUPN, deviceID)])
        
        dfNewDevicesGen = dfNewDevicesGen.union(newRow)


display(dfNewDevicesGen.limit(10))

# Added a few more rows of random people in order to have someone with 4 or 3 devices; can add more.
newRow1 = spark.createDataFrame([("LAPTOP-2839STV", "Intune", "Personal", "Compliant", "Windows", "10.0.22118.1000", "2021-10-12 16:13:03.8803119", "debrasmith1@contosoisd3.onmicrosoft.com", "a6383dc9-9f8e-4ca2-9318-afd9b604554e")])
newRow2 = spark.createDataFrame([("SMILEY2821", "Intune", "Unknown", "Not Evaluated", "iOS/iPadOS", "0.0.0.0", "2021-09-21 18:07:48.0000000", "debrasmith1@contosoisd3.onmicrosoft.com", "10c83379-b0a6-f632-d378-7ac9b603e724")])
newRow3 = spark.createDataFrame([("DESKTOP-UPD28", "Intune", "Unknown", "Compliant", "Windows", "10.0.22000.120", "2021-10-08 04:09:03.0000000", "maxwelljones6@contosoisd3.onmicrosoft.com", "dd61d4b8-35af-cc53-d298-1e977a8433aa")])
newRow4 = spark.createDataFrame([("LAPTOP-SHELL43", "Intune", "Personal", "Compliant", "Windows", "10.0.22000.176", "2021-09-17 18:36:03.9886625", "shelbyberger1@contosoisd3.onmicrosoft.com", "2442a3a8-c25d-920a-f031-ba196a8c93ff")])

dfNewDevicesGen = dfNewDevicesGen.union(newRow1)
dfNewDevicesGen = dfNewDevicesGen.union(newRow2)
dfNewDevicesGen = dfNewDevicesGen.union(newRow3)
dfNewDevicesGen = dfNewDevicesGen.union(newRow4)
display(dfNewDevicesGen)
